Statistical Anomalies Analysis

Key Findings and Statistical Anomalies

2020 Election Anomalies

  • Record turnout rate of 62.8%, exceeding 2σ above mean
  • Largest vote increase between elections (+21.7M)
  • Highest major party vote totals in history

1992 Third Party Phenomenon

  • Perot captured 19.7% of votes
  • 4x higher than typical third-party performance
  • Coincided with high turnout (55.2%)

Turnout Patterns

  • Mean turnout: 55.1%
  • Standard deviation: 4.2%
  • Unusual 1996 dip to 48.1%
  • Consistent upward trend 1996-2020

Population vs. Voting Trends

  • Vote totals growing faster than population
  • 2016-2020: 15.9% vote increase vs 2.6% population growth
  • Widening gap between total and eligible population

Conclusions

The data reveals several significant trends in US voting patterns. There's a clear increase in political engagement over time, with barriers to voting participation apparently decreasing. The 2020 election stands out as particularly anomalous, showing unprecedented levels of participation despite (or perhaps due to) the unique circumstances of that year. The declining success of third-party candidates after the 1992 Perot campaign, with only a minor resurgence in 2016, suggests increasing polarization in the two-party system.

Data sourced from official election records and US Census Bureau statistics

Analysis based on available data from 1988-2020 presidential elections
